<DOC><DOCNO> AP880610-0283 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 1608EDT</FILEID><FIRST>s i BC-Summit-Expectations Adv12-1stadd   06-10 0436</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Summit-Expectations, Adv 12-1st add,0453</SECOND><NOTE>$Adv12</NOTE><NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 12, and Thereafter</NOTE><HEAD>UNDATED: of pollution.</HEAD><HEAD>JAPAN</HEAD><TEXT>   Japanese Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita wants to focusattention on his country's contributions to the internationalcommunity.   Takeshita also will stress that Japan has contributed to theimprovement in the global economy through its macroeconomicperformance. A new economic plan has forecast a growth in thecountry's gross national product of 3.75 percent.   ``Our economy is in very good shape. The external imbalance ...is now being adjusted and Japan is contributing to bettermanagement of the world economy,'' a government official said at anews conference Thursday. He said imports of manufactured goodswere rising, the country's markets were opening and thedistribution systems were changing.   The official, who spoke on condition he not be identified, saidTakeshita and Foreign Minister Sosuke Uno ``will take concreteaction to advance the Uruguay Round at the Toronto summit.''   Japan will also urge other summit participants to put out a``strong message'' against the rising trend in protectionism.   To demonstrate its growing role as a bridge between Asia and theWest, it will argue on behalf of the newly industrialized economies(NIEs) of South Korea, Taiwan, Hong Kong and Singapore.   ``We have to admit that the NIEs have positively contributed tothe advancement of the world economy ... that they are the hopesfor the developing world,'' the official said.</TEXT><HEAD>WEST GERMANY</HEAD><TEXT>   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl said before the meeting thathe expects the summit to produce a ``clear signal toward achievingstability and trust of the markets.''   He said he will press the United States to reduce its budgetdeficit and Japan to open further its markets.   Kohl said West Germany would intensify efforts to boost itsdomestic demand in an effort to reduce trade imbalances.   He said he will propose a series of measures to further reducethe debt burden of the world's poorest nations at the summit.   West Germany this month announced that it was forgiving 86million marks ($50.5 million) of debts owed by some of the world'spoorest nations.   A senior government official said West Germany expected thesummit to be ``one of relative harmony,'' focusing on long-termways to solve major world economic problems.   Kohl is also expected to urge caution in the cutting of Europeanagricultural subsidies.   On agricultural subsidies, West Germany is more cautious than,say, the British. Kohl has warned that cuts agreed by the 12-nationEuropean Economic Community decision in February to cutoverproduction ``will not be easy to implement.''</TEXT><NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 12</NOTE><TEXT/></DOC>